Thank you . ] Call for Papers Workshop on Agent-mediated Electronic Commerce ( AmEC- 98 ) International Conference on Electronic Commerce ( ICEC- 98 ) April 6 - 9 , Seoul , Korea http : / / ecommerce . media . mit . edu / icec-amec DESCRIPTION Over the past two years , a new kind of software application has appeared based on a synthesis of ideas from artificial intelligence , human-computer interaction and electronic transactions : agents that help mediate electronic commerce activities . Agents differ from "traditional" software in that they are personalized , autonomous , proactive , and adaptive . These qualities make agents particularly useful for the information-rich and process-rich environment of electronic commerce . Software agents enable new types of transactions . For example , the elusive one-to-one marketing becomes more of a reality when consumer agents capture and share ( or sell ) consumer demographics . Prices and other transaction dimensions need no longer to be fixed ; selling agents can dynamically tailor merchant offerings to each consumer . Economies of scale become feasible in new markets when agents negotiate on special arbitration contracts . Dynamic business relationships will give rise to more competitively agile organizations . It is these new opportunities combined with substantial reductions in transaction costs that will revolutionize electronic commerce . Software agents will play an increasing variety of roles as mediators in electronic commerce . This workshop will explore these roles , their supporting technologies , and how they relate to electronic commerce in its three main forms : business-to-business , business-to-consumer , and consumer-to-consumer transactions . TOPICS Topics of interest include but are not limited to : * distributed marketplaces * open and extensible languages and protocols for locating and defining goods and services * merchant differentiation * value-based product comparisons * buying decision aids * brokering * negotiation * visualization of marketplace data and activities * trust and reputation * security * financial and investment transactions * payment mechanisms * advertising and marketing * ontologies * online catalogs * intermediaries TIMING This is an exciting and important time for agent-mediated electronic commerce systems . While some projects have been around for several years , there has been an explosion of new efforts in recent months - - both academically and commercially . Even mainstream e-commerce Web sites are now incorporating agent-based features . This is a vital time to assess the state-of-the-art , technology trends , and the business , technical , and social issues that are most critical to successfully engage agents in electronic commerce . FORMAT Based on the participants' submissions we will select and focus on three areas of common interest . The workshop will include short presentations , moderated discussions and a birds-of-a-feather session . We plan to organize a panel to discuss real-world experiences and problems with agent-mediated electronic commerce systems comprised of panelists from industry and academia . ATTENDANCE AND SUBMISSION REQUIREMENTS Participation will be by position statement acceptance only and will be limited to approximately 30 people . Applicants should submit a short bio and either a position statement ( up to one page ) or an extended abstract ( up to three pages . ) Entries should include presentation media requirements and indicate a desire to present software demonstrations along with the computer requirements . We are arranging for the full papers of outstanding extended abstracts to appear in an edited collection of papers - - a special issue of a journal or a book . ( subject to the quality , topic and number of papers ) .
